<h5>Wired</h5>
<h4><a href="//www.wired.com/2015/04/silk-road-1/">Online Outlaw</a></h4>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">There is just about no story more delicious than the saga of Silk Road, the highly clandestine online marketplace for drugs. It was run by a secret mastermind whose nom de guerre, Dread Pirate Roberts, was plucked from the &#8220;Princess Bride.&#8221; D.P.R., as his friends called him, ordered assassinations as easily as if he were ordering pizza. Much has been written about the rise and fall of Silk Road, but Joshuah Bearman takes a step back and tells the story as a cops-and-robbers thriller with real cinematic verve. Read it now before it becomes a movie â the rights sold before the article was published. <a href="https://www.twitter.com/samdolnick">â Sam Dolnick</a></p>
<div class="w50 right">
<img src="https://static01.nyt.com/projects/ray_mailer/heads/KannapellHead.png"/>
</div>
<h5> Facebook </h5>
<h4><a href="https://www.facebook.com/marcitarrantjohnson">Also in Baltimore</a></h4>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What happened to the scores of people arrested in Baltimore this week can only be a footnote to the death of Freddie Gray. But a public defender&#8217;s Facebook post about the conditions in which they were held â 15 people in a 10 by 10-foot cell, no indication of charges â makes that footnote scorching. <a href="https://www.twitter.com/AKannapell">â Andrea Kannapell</a></p>
<div class="w50 right">
<img src="https://static01.nyt.com/projects/ray_mailer/heads/LuoHead.png"/>
</div>
<h5>The Atlantic</h5>
<h4><a href="//www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2015/05/the-upwardly-mobile-barista/389513/">Starbucks U.</a></h4>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">I found so much of this piece fascinating and important, particularly as we think about economic inequality and the importance of a college education in today&#8217;s economy. The article examines Starbucks&#8217;s experiment in paying for the college educations of its baristas, but its main argument has to do with how colleges have been atrocious at customer service â a major reason people on the lower end of the economic spectrum, in particular, often wind up not finishing college. Another fascinating, unrelated nugget in the article? That Starbucks hires only 4 percent of job applicants. A lower acceptance rate than Harvard! <a href="https://www.twitter.com/michaelluo">â Michael Luo</a></p>
<div class="w50 right">
<img src="https://static01.nyt.com/projects/ray_mailer/heads/WorthamHead.png"/>
</div>
<h5>Model View Culture</h5>
<h4><a href="https://modelviewculture.com/news/lets-talk-about-pay">#TalkPay</a></h4>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">A hashtag movement is promoting wage equality through transparency online, encouraging people to talk honestly about what they make. Should be really fascinating to watch it unfold over the weekend. <a href="https://www.twitter.com/jennydeluxe">â Jenna Wortham</a><br />
<span id="more-2335"></span></p>
<div class="w50 right">
<img src="https://static01.nyt.com/projects/ray_mailer/heads/BloomHead.png"/>
</div>
<h5>The Economist</h5>
<h4><a href="//www.economist.com/blogs/prospero/2015/04/70-years-ago-today">Wagging the Long Tail</a></h4>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">It seems as if a lot of publications right now are trying to find clever new ways to cover old events and resurface past material. This look at a 70-year-old photo had a smart and fresh approach â it&#8217;s a snapshot of a person and moment in history, expertly written. <a href="https://www.twitter.com/Julesm_b">â Julie Bloom</a></p>
<div class="w50 right">
<img src="https://static01.nyt.com/projects/ray_mailer/heads/EstrinHead.png"/>
</div>
<h5>David-Campbell.org</h5>
<h4><a href="https://www.david-campbell.org/2015/04/30/photojournalism-advocacy-change-marcus-bleasdale-human-rights-watch-central-african-republic/">Finding the Right Frame</a></h4>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When the Overseas Press Club gave one of its top awards to the British photographer Marcus Bleasdale this week for his work in the Central African Republic, it set off a lot of debate about activism and objectivity. After all, it was the first time the Robert Capa Award had gone to someone working for an NGO â in this case, Human Rights Watch. This consideration by a professor who analyzes visual storytelling responds to several articles about the issue, including my own in the Lens blog. He argues forcefully that transparency is the only guarantor of honest reporting. <a href="https://www.twitter.com/JamesEstrin">â James Estrin</a></p>
